        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution is chosen to match our images in polarimetric differential imaging (VLT/NACO). Since these images have a resolution of 0.09 arcseconds, a proper comparison can be performed only by means of images with 0.1 arcsec. The only band that can achieve this resolution is Band 9. One of the main point of our observations is to determine the exact location of the inner cavity. To do that, a sensitivity ten times lower than the expected intensity per beam at the cavity edge is sufficient to claim the cavity. To calculate the intensity at the edge, we use the disk model by Andrews et al (2011) applied to the SMA observations of this source. The surface mass density at the cavity edge turns, in Band 9, into an intensity of 66 mJy/beam (assuming a realistic value for the temperature of 60 K). A 3sigma detection of the cavity is therefore expected for a sensitivity higher than 66 : (3x10)=2.2 mJy. However, the estimated observing time does not change down to 1.3 mJy. This motivated us to require this sensitivity and guarantee a detection of the cavity up to 5sigma. Since the project is focusing on the continuum, we use the largest possible bandwidth. From previous SMA observations, we know that the extent of the emission is smaller than 1.2 arcsec and, therefore, we need a single 12-m array configuration.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
