    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We aim at performing a high-resolution comparison of the spatial distribution of small and large dust grains in the transitional disk around SAO206462. These disks show large inner cavities that may be due to the interaction with orbiting companion(s). In this scenario, the dynamics of small (micron-size) and large (mm-size) dust grains is expected to differ. We are especially motivated by the discovery of important discrepancies in the disk of SAO 206462 between our polarimetric differential imaging (PDI) VLT/NACO observations (Garufi et al. 2013) and thermal 850 micron SMA images (Brown et al. 2009). In particular, different cavity sizes (28 vs 39 AU respectively) suggests that the mechanism responsible for sculpting the disk must also differentiate the dust distribution. We claim that a single giant planet (of 10 jupiter masses) is consistent with our observations. Furthermore, the peak of the thermal images lies where PDI images show minima. This might be a tangible clue towards grain growth. However, the investigation of these discrepancies is limited by the angular resolution of the SMA data (0.5’’ times 0.25’’), that is not adequate to that of our PDI images (0.09’’). </prp:abstract>
